claude-sonnet.text:
At Matignon, Pompidou put forth a social status quo to unions, but found no luck. In Biafra, racial strife; in Conakry, talk of a coup. A typhoon struck Nagasaki, whilst a storm known as Amanda was approaching Tristan da Cunha, from which cargo aircraft took all inhabitants away. At Roland-Garros, finally, in a Davis Cup match, Santana won against Darmon, six-to-third, first-to-sixth, third-to-sixth, to-an-final-count-of-six.

Turning off his radio, squatting on his rug, taking a long gasp, doing pull-ups - about half a dozen - but tiring too fast, sitting down, worn out, gazing dully at that puzzling drawing that would show up or vanish on that tapistry according to how his sight would focus:

Thus, at points, a ring, not fully round, finishing with a flat mark: similar to a big G as shown in a looking glass.

Or, pallid against pallid, arising from crystalloid fog, a proud portrait of a king holding up a spiky staff.

Or, for a flash, amid straight marks, a rough draft's arrival, not satisfying: jutting stand-ins, hybrid outlines showing, in a futility of fancy, a Sardon's laughing Hand with its trio of digits.

Or, abruptly dominating, an illustration of a fat bumbling wasp, carrying upon its black thorax a trio of almost lily-white joints.

His mind would drift. As focus took hold, studying his rug, his brain found five, six, twenty, six-and-twenty combinations, fascinating drafts but without gravity, flimsy slips, dark portraits that his mind would sort again and again, hunting for a sign that was solid, a total sign that would instantly grant him clarity; a sign to satisfy him, though what was shown was a path of odd links, a lot of impurity in drafts, of which all, you might say, built up and wove toward a primary draft's form that it mimics, that it follows, that it nigh attains but always hushes:

a corpse, a thug, a portrait of him;
a young bull, a stupid hawk, a small bird warming its sanctuary;
a rheumatic knot;
a wish;
